   <titles>
      <title>Points, Arrows, and Vectors</title>
      <plain.title>Points, Arrows, Vectors</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>An <subordinate>
                     <hot>arrow</hot>
                     <companion>
                        <unit.ref unitId="Sub_ArrowsIllustration"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Illustration</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Pictures of arrows.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </companion>
                  </subordinate> is a convenient tool to express the location of one point in relation to another. The location of an arrow in space is completely determined by the location of its tail, its length and its direction. If we allow the arrow to move in space while keeping its length and its direction, we obtain a vector.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>We will see that this feature renders vectors an extremely versatile tool in our efforts to describe the world around us.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <legitimate.children>
      <unit unitid="SubSec_Arrows">
         <titles>
            <title>Arrows</title>
            <plain.title>Arrows</plain.title>
         </titles>
         <body>
            <block>
               <block.body>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_Arrow">
                     <caption>Arrow</caption>
                     <associate type="Illustration">
                        <unit.ref unitId="Sub_ArrowsIllustration"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>An illustration of arrows</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>An arrow 
					in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math> is given by listing two points <math>
                                 <latex>P</latex>
                              </math> and <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math> of <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math> in order. The first point <math>
                                 <latex>P</latex>
                              </math> is called the tail of the arrow. The second point <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math> is called the tip of the arrow. We write <math>
                                 <latex>\Arrw{PQ}</latex>
                              </math>
					to denote the arrow joining <math>
                                 <latex>P</latex>
                              </math> to <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                           <index.symbol>
                              <symbol>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\Arrw{PQ}</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </symbol>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The arrow in <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                       </math> joining point <math>
                                          <latex>P</latex>
                                       </math> to point <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.symbol>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>arrow</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>in <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                       </math>, joining point <math>
                                          <latex>P</latex>
                                       </math> to point <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                                 <para align="center">
                                    <para.body>Click to see the definition of arrow.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The length of an arrow is the distance between its end points:</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <def id="Def_ArrowLength">
                     <caption>Length of an Arrow</caption>
                     <associate type="Illustration">
                        <unit.ref unitId="Illu_ArrowLength"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Illustration of Length of an Arrow</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <associate type="Example">
                        <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_ArrowLength"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Example</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Examples of computing the length of an arrow</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Given points <math>
                                 <latex>P(x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                              </math> and <math>
                                 <latex>Q(y_1,\dots ,y_n)</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math>, the length of the arrow
					<math>
                                 <latex>\Arrow{P}{Q}</latex>
                              </math> from <math>
                                 <latex>P</latex>
                              </math> to <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math> is
					</para.body>
                           <index.symbol>
                              <symbol>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\Length{\Arrow{P}{Q} }</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </symbol>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>length of the arrow joining <math>
                                          <latex>P</latex>
                                       </math> to <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.symbol>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>length</term>
                              <term>of an arrow</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The length of an arrow is the distance between its end points. - Definition of the concept.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>arrow</term>
                              <term>length</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The length of an arrow is the distance between its end points. - Definition of the concept.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                        <math.display>
                           <latex>\Length{\Arrow{P}{Q} }\ :=\ \Dstnc{P}{Q}\ =\ \sqrt{(y_1-x_1)^2+\cdots +(y_n-x_n)^2}.</latex>
                        </math.display>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
               </block.body>
